        <Parent_String>dolls (figurines) [300211087], figurines [300047455], sculpture by subject type [300047409], sculpture (visual works) [300047090], visual works by material or technique [300191091], visual works (works) [300191086], Visual Works (hierarchy name) [300179869], Visual and Verbal Communication (hierarchy name) [300264552], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Fertility figures, usually female, of abstracted form, with disk-like heads with high oval foreheads and most often having horizontal arms, cylindrical torso, breasts, and navel; among Asante of West Africa believed to ensure conception and successful birth.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000039271/Sieber and Walker, African Art (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Úsese para estatuillas de fertilidad, usualmente femeninas de formas abstractas, con cabezas en forma de disco con frente alta y oval y la mayoría con brazos horizontales, torso, pecho y ombligo cilíndrico; entre los Asante de África occidental creían que aseguraba la concepción y un nacimiento exitoso.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Te gebruiken voor, gewoonlijk vrouwelijke, vruchtbaarheidsfiguren, abstract van vorm, met een schijfvormig hoofd, een hoog ovaal voorhoofd en meestal horizontale armen, een cilindervormige romp, borsten en navel; garanderen naar de overtuiging van de Asante in West-Afrika de bevruchting en een voorspoedige geboorte.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Fruchtbarkeitsfigur, gewöhnlich weiblich, in abstrakter Form gestaltet, mit einem scheibenartigen Kopf und hoher ovaler Stirn, oft mit horizontal ausgestreckten Armen, einem zylindrischen Rumpf, Brüsten und Bauchnabel; unter den Aschanti in West-Afrika herrscht der Glaube, dass die Figur Empfängnis und glückliche Geburt bewirkt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>象徵生育能力的抽象化人偶，通常為女性形象，頭部為圓盤狀，具橢圓狀的高額頭，多半具有水平舉起的手臂、圓柱狀軀幹、乳房和肚臍；西非的阿善提人相信，這種人偶可保祐婦女求子和順產。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Figuras de fertilidade, geralmente femininas, de forma abstrata, com cabeças que parecem discos com testas grandes ovais e frequentemente com braços horizontais, torso cilíndrico, seios e umbigo; entre o povo Asante do oeste da África, acreditava-se que garantia uma concepção e um nascimento bem-sucedidos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000179/VP-intern</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000110648/Portuguese Translation Intern Project (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
